%I A396048 #21 May 19 2026 17:52:28
%S A396048 0,0,1,5,45,1270,107387,29903617
%N A396048 Number of equivalence classes of full-rank n-element subsets of complement pairs in the n-dimensional Boolean hypercube under coordinate permutation.
%C A396048 Let V = {0,1}^n be the vertices of the n-dimensional Boolean hypercube. A complement pair is a set {v, ~v} where ~v is the bitwise negation of v. We consider the set of all 2^(n-1) - 1 complement pairs, excluding the trivial pair {(0...0), (1...1)}.
%C A396048 We select a subset of exactly n pairs. A subset is considered "full-rank" if there exists at least one way to choose a representative vector from each of the n pairs such that the resulting n x n matrix has a nonzero determinant over the real numbers.
%C A396048 The symmetric group S_n acts on these subsets by permuting the n coordinate axes. This sequence gives the number of distinct orbits (equivalence classes) under this group action.
%C A396048 For n=1, excluding the trivial pair leaves 0 available pairs, so a(1) = 0.
%C A396048 For n=2, excluding the trivial pair leaves 1 available pair. We must choose n=2 pairs, which is impossible, so a(2) = 0.
%C A396048 For n=3, there are 3 available pairs. We choose 3, yielding exactly 1 subset, which is full-rank. Thus a(3) = 1.
%C A396048 The terms a(1) through a(8) were computed using parallelized depth-first search with lexicographical symmetry pruning, and verified up to a(6) using Burnside's Lemma over the conjugacy classes of S_n.
%H A396048 M. A. Harrison, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/T-C.1973.223649">On the number of classes of binary matrices</a>, IEEE Trans. Computers, 22 (1973), 1048-1051. doi:10.1109/T-C.1973.223649.
%H A396048 M. A. Harrison, <a href="/A000711/a000711.pdf">On the number of classes of binary matrices</a>, IEEE Transactions on Computers, C-22.12 (1973), 1048-1052. (Annotated scanned copy)
%H A396048 Adrien Mabire, <a href="https://github.com/NadranEr/binary-basis-classification">C++ codes</a>, GitHub.
%e A396048 For n=1, the only possible vectors are {0} and {1}. Both are 0s and 1s so they are are excluded => a(1)=0.
%e A396048 For n=2, {01} and {10} are equivalent leaving a single vector so the set cannot be full rank => a(2)=0.
%e A396048 For n=3, the valid canonical vectors are {001},{010},{011}. {011} and {100} are equivalent which makes the set equivalent to {001},{010},{100} which is valid. Those are the only possible vectors => a(3)=1.
%K A396048 nonn,hard,more,new
%O A396048 1,4
%A A396048 _Adrien Mabire_, May 14 2026
